\date{2026-04-07}
\title{#{\Delta^1}-discrete types are triangulated Segal types, and those are left Segal}
\author{fredrikbakke}
\contributor{samueltoth}
\meta{external}{https://github.com/samtoth/agda-synthetic-categories/pull/87}
\tag{changelog}
\import{stt-macros}

\subtree{\title{Summary}

\p{
We formalise some connections between [#{\Delta^1}-discrete types](stt-00B6),
[triangulated types](stt-00LD), and [Segal types](stt-00AI), and consequently obtain
corollaries for groupoids and precategories.
}

\p{
Let's recall the definitions.
We say a type is #{\Delta^1}-discrete if it is #{\Delta^1}-null, and a
[groupoid](stt-00L7) if it is additionally [simplicial](stt-00AC), i.e., for all
elements #{i} and #{j} of #{\Delta^1} it is [null](stt-005G) at the proposition
#{(i \le j) \vee (j \le i)}. As a generalisation of simpliciality we say a type is
[triangulated](stt-00LD) if it is [local](stt-005F) at the triangulated square
inclusion #{\Delta^2\amalg_{\Delta^1}\Delta^2 \to \Delta^1 \times \Delta^1}. Note
that being simplicial is the same as being null at the fibres of this map,
[which is a stronger condition](stt-00CS). It turns out that without additional
assumptions, #{\Delta^1}-discrete types are already triangulated and Segal, which is
sufficient for proving many of the basic properties of categories, like
[the Yoneda lemma](fre-0001). In fact, if we only want the \em{covariant} Yoneda
lemma, we can get away with a condition that we show is even weaker than triangulated
Segalness: [left Segalness](stt-00DA). This is locality with respect to the inner
horn inclusion into the cone of #{\Delta^1}, rather than the type #{\Delta^2}.
}

\p{
Concretely, we formalise the implications
\ol{
\li{#{\Delta^1}-discrete types are triangulated \ref{stt-00LE}}
\li{#{\Delta^1}-discrete types are Segal \ref{stt-00LF}}
\li{triangulated Segal types are left Segal \ref{stt-00DG}.}
}

These connections give the dotted implications to the following diagram
\quiver{
\begin{tikzcd}
\mathrm{Grpd} && \Delta^1\mathrm{Disc} \\
\\
\mathrm{Precat} && \mathrm{TriangSegal} && \mathrm{Segal} \\
\\
&& \mathrm{LeftSegal}
\arrow[Rightarrow, from=1-1, to=1-3]
\arrow[Rightarrow, from=1-3, to=3-3, dotted]
\arrow[Rightarrow, from=1-1, to=3-1, dotted]
\arrow[Rightarrow, from=3-1, to=3-3]
\arrow[Rightarrow, from=3-3, to=3-5]
\arrow[Rightarrow, from=5-3, to=3-5]
\arrow[Rightarrow, from=3-3, to=5-3, dotted]
\end{tikzcd}
}
}
}
